===Etymology===
The etymology is unclear, but the word probably has Romany origins – compare Romany [[chavi]] ‘male child’, [[chavo]] ‘female child’, [[chal]] ‘boy’, [[chavvy]] ‘mate, friend’.  It thus may be related to [[charva]] (from Romany [[charver]] ‘prostitute’), and Spanish [[chaval]] (which does not have pejorative connotations).  It seems to have originated in the south-east and may represent a development of, or influence from, certain towns names including [[w:Chatham|Chatham]] (which has a Romany community), [[w:Cheltenham|Cheltenham]] or [[w:Chaddesden|Chaddesden]].  More doubtful theories include the notion that it comes from Nigerian-London slang [[chaff]] ‘lower-class person’.  As the word became more widespread, a variety of [[backronym]]s have also been suggested ('''C'''ouncil '''H'''ouse '''A'''nd '''V'''iolent, '''C'''ouncil '''H'''ouse '''A'''ssociated '''V'''ermin, etc.), all equally unsubstantiated.

chavs smell like weewee

===Pronunciation===
* /tʃæv/ 

===Noun===
'''chav''' (''plural'' '''chavs''')

#(''British, derogatory, informal'') An urban working-class youth: especially as associated with aggression, poor education, and a perceived ‘common’ taste in clothing and lifestyle.

